-- Regression: owner_sym->decl_node blind cast in super handler.
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 65 AUDIT-01 Top-20 rank 10 (rows 10a
-- and 10b) flagged two call sites in src/analyzer/resolve.c (the 'super'
-- expression handler) where the current method's owner symbol decl_node
-- was cast to Iron_ObjectDecl without a preceding kind check. Iron
-- supports methods on enums (`func Dir.is_vertical()`), so
-- `current_method->owner_sym` can resolve to a symbol whose decl_node is
-- Iron_EnumDecl or Iron_InterfaceDecl. The unconditional cast then
-- misread `extends_name` at a foreign offset (for EnumDecl this is the
-- `variants[]` header pointer, producing a garbage string fed to
-- scope_lookup).
--
-- **Layout Diagram.**
--   Iron_ObjectDecl: { span, kind, name, fields[], field_count, extends_name, ... }
--   Iron_EnumDecl:   { span, kind, name, variants[], variant_count, ... }
--
--   Reading od->extends_name at the EnumDecl layout offset returns
--   whatever pointer happens to sit at the variants[] header address —
--   typically a heap array pointer that looks like a garbage string when
--   fed to iron_scope_lookup as a type name.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** resolve.c (super handler) now checks
-- decl_node->kind == IRON_NODE_OBJECT_DECL before the cast and emits a
-- clean diagnostic for the enum/interface-owner case. Both cast sites
-- (the initial extends_name check at ~resolve.c:240 and the parent
-- lookup at ~resolve.c:255) call IRON_NODE_ASSERT_KIND before casting
-- to Iron_ObjectDecl. PROT-04, Phase 66 Plan 03.
--
-- **Severity.** H. Affects every enum method (`func EnumType.method()`)
-- where the body references `super`, and every interface-method context
-- where owner_sym resolves to a non-object declaration.
--
-- **Note on fixture coverage.** Iron's typecheck/HIR layers do not
-- currently wire `super.method()` end-to-end — attempting
-- `return super.foo()` inside a method body reports a Void-vs-Int return
-- mismatch because super is parsed but the method-on-parent lookup is
-- not implemented. This fixture therefore exercises the positive
-- `object Dog extends Animal` path through resolve.c (parsing, symbol
-- creation, method owner wiring) without dereferencing `super`. The new
-- IRON_NODE_ASSERT_KIND gate in resolve.c's super handler is the
-- structural protection: any future code path that surfaces `super`
-- through resolve.c with a non-object owner will abort via iron_ice in
-- Debug builds rather than silently misreading memory.

object Animal {
    val tag: Int
}

object Dog extends Animal {
    val breed: Int
}

func Dog.describe() -> Int {
    val local = 1
    return local + self.breed
}

func Animal.get_kind() -> Int {
    return 7
}

func main() {
    val d = Dog(42)
    println("dog.describe: {d.describe()}")
    val a = Animal(3)
    println("animal.kind: {a.get_kind()}")
}
